Surrealism — "wave of dreams" — new art of flaneiie. New nineteenth-century 
past — Paris its classic locale. Here, fashion has opened the place of dialectical 
exchange between woman and ware. The clerk, death, tall and loutish, measures 
the century by the yard, serves as mannequin himself to save costs, and manages 
single-handedly the "liquidation" that in French is called "revolution." <See f °,1 
and Bl,4.> And all this we know only since yesterday. We look on the empty 
offices, and where <?> yesterday there was <?>... a room. <D°,1> 

Fashion was never any tiling other than: provocation of death through the woman. Here, 
with the victory of death, this provocation has ended. Deadi has erected the armature of 
the whores as a pallid battle memorial on the banks of the new Lethe, which as river of 
asphalt nins through the arcades. <See f°,l and Bl,4.> <D°,2> 

And nothing at all of what we are saying here actually existed. None of it has ever 
lived — as surely as a skeleton has never lived, but only a man. As surely, how- 
ever, <broken off> <D*,3 > 

Being past, being no more, is passionately at work in things. To this the historian 
trusts for his subject matter. He depends on this force, and knows things as they 
are at the moment of their ceasing to be. Arcades are such monuments of being- 
no-more. And the energy that works in them is dialectics. The dialectic takes its 
way through the arcades, ransacking them, revolutionizing them, turns them 
upside down and inside out, converting them, since they no longer remain what 
they are, from abodes of luxury to <x>. And nothing of them lasts except tire 
name: passages. And: Passage du Panorama <sic>. In the inmost recesses of these 
names the upheaval is working, and therefore we hold a world in the names of 
old streets, and to read the name of a street at night is like undergoing a transfor- 
mation <?>. <D',4> 



