"It has often happened to me to note certain trivial events passing before my eyes 
as showing a quite original aspect, in which I fondly hoped to discern the spirit of 
the period. 'This,' I would tell myself, 'was bound to happen today and could not 
have been other than it is. It is a sign of the times.' Well, nine times out of ten, I 
have come across the very same event with analogous circumstances in old 
memoirs or old history books." A. France, Le Jardin d'Epicure, p. 113. 27 <See 
Sl,2.> <G°,4> 

The figure of the flaneur. He resembles the hashish eater, takes space up into 
himself like the latter. In hashish intoxication, the space starts winking at us: 
"What do you think may have gone on here?" And with the very same question, 
space accosts the flaneur. <See Mla,3.> In no other city can he answer it as 
precisely as he can here. For of no other city has more been written, and more is 
known here about certain stretches of the city's streets than elsewhere about the 
history of entire countries. <G°,5> 



