The deepest enchantment of the collector: to put things under a spell, as though at a 
touch of the magic wand, so that all at once, while a last shudder runs over them, they are 
transfixed. All architecture becomes pedestal, socle, frame, antique memory room. It must 
not be assumed that the collector, the flaneur, would fmd anything strange in the topos 
hjpermiranios — that place beyond the heavens where Plato locates the immutable arche- 
types of things. He loses himself, assuredly. But in return, he has the strength to raise 
liimself up again to his full height — thanks to a project <?>. From out of the mists that 



envelop his sun, images arise like tables of the gods, islands in the Mediterranean. <See 
Hla,2.> <L°,31> 



