Of particular importance, the great "legend" with which Wiertz has accompanied his 
Rnsees et visions d'une tete coupee (Thoughts and Visions of a Severed Head). The first 
thing that strikes one about this magnetopathic experience is the grandiose sleight of hand 
which the consciousness executes in death. "What a singular thing! The head is here 
under the scaffold, and it believes that it still exists above, forming part of the body, and 
continuing to wait for the blow that will separate it from the trunk." A.J. Wiertz, Oeuvres 
littercdres (Paris, 1870), p. 492. (At work here in Wiertz is the same inspiration that ani- 
mates the unforgettable short story by Ambrose Bierce.' 18 The rebel who is hanged from a 
bridge over the river.) <See K2a,2.> <0°,19> 

