Great collectors. Pachinger, Wolfskehl's friend, who has put together a collection that, in 
its array of proscribed and damaged objects, rivals the Figdor collection in Vienna. On the 
Stachus, he suddenly stoops to pick up something he has been seeking for weeks: a 
misprinted streetcar ticket that was in circulation for only one hour. Gratz in Wiihlgarten. 
The family in which everyone collects something, for example matchboxes. Pachinger 
hardly knows any more how things stand in the world; explains to his visitors — alongside 
the most antique implements — the use of pocket handkerchief s, distorting mirrors, and 
the like. "Beautiful foundation for a collection." Hoerschelmann. A German in Paris who 
collects bad (only bad!) art. <See H2a,2.> <0°,29> 

Waxworks: mixture of the ephemeral and the fashionable. Woman fastening her garter. 
