Hoffmann as type of the flaneur. "Des Vetters Eckfenster" <My Cousin's Comer Win- 
dow) the testament of the flaneur. Thus Hoffmann's great success in France. In the 
biographical notes to the five-volume collection of his later writings, we read: "Hoffmann 
was never really a friend of the great outdoors . What mattered to him more than anything 
else was the human being — communication with, observations about, the simple sight of, 
human beings. Whenever he went for a walk in summer, which in good weather hap- 
pened every day toward evening, he always made for those public places where he would 
run into people. On the way, there was scarcely a tavern or pastry shop where he would 
not look in to see whedier anyone — and if so, who — might be there." <See M4a,2.) 

