"covered place," which in turn is traced back to an Indo-European root signifying "to 
cover, conceal." "Hall" is cognate with "hell." In earlier times, the hall — in contrast to 



the room — was a spacious, half -open structure (with a roof supported by pillars or 
columns) designed to provide shelter from rain or sun. 

