9. Tlie title of this poem, which appears in a collection signed by "Savinien Lapointe, 
Workman Cobbler," and introduced by Sue, plays on the double meaning of edioppe, 



"workshop" and "graver" or "burin" (the tool used by a cobbler to engrave on 
leather). In an engraving that accompanies the poem, Lapointe is shown working 
leather in his shop and, in a caption, lauding Sue as "an eminent surgeon wielding the 
scalpel" that will remove France's social ills — "scalpel" deriving from the same Latin 
root as eclioppe. The work is thus a poem in praise of Sue's scalpel from the eclioppe of 
Lapointe in both senses. 

