"The Arcades of Paris" 

1. See note 2 in Convolute H. 

2. Seitenhimmeln, possibly an error in transcription; in Q3,2, Benjamin has Seidenhim- 
meln, "silken skies." And in the third sentence of tliis passage, instead of Land, Q3,2 
reads Band, "ribbon." See "Moonlit Nights on the Rue la Boetie," in SW, vol. 2, 
pp. 107-108. 

3. In German, List, which originally meant "knowledge" and refeired to techniques of 
hunting and war, to magical abilities and artistic skill. 

4. Greek name for Castor and Pollux, twin sons of Leda who were transformed by Zeus 
into the constellation Gemini. They had a cult in Lacedaemon, where they were 
symbolized by the dokana, two upright pieces of wood coimected by two crossbeams. 
Presumably an allusion to Benjamin's collaboration with Franz Hessel. 

